---
import ResearchLayout from '../../layouts/ResearchLayout.astro';
import { RESEARCH_PAPERS } from '../../lib/research-nav.ts';
---

<ResearchLayout
  title="Research"
  description="The field-ui research paper family — preprint drafts on the concepts behind a relational field runtime for the DOM."
>
  <h1 data-body="attract" data-strength="0.6" data-feedback>field-ui research</h1>

  <p class="lede">
    A small family of focused papers on the ideas behind <a href="/">field-ui</a>, a platform-native
    relational field runtime for the DOM. One flagship paper names the paradigm; the others each
    validate one specific claim.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    <p><strong>Preprint drafts — work in progress.</strong> These are technical-preprint drafts, not
    finished, peer-reviewed publications. They carry status banners, some citations are still
    placeholders, and <strong>no user-study results have been collected</strong> — the empirical
    papers present study <em>designs</em> and hypotheses, never measured outcomes. The canonical
    source is <a href="https://github.com/zachshallbetter/field-ui/tree/main/docs/research">
    <code>docs/research/</code></a> in the repository.</p>
  </blockquote>

  <h2>The unifying thesis</h2>
  <p>
    Interfaces are not only layouts of components. They are <strong>relational fields of meaning.</strong>
    field-ui makes those fields <em>executable, inspectable, accessible, and authorable</em> on top of
    semantic HTML — and the research question is whether a field-based model can improve orientation,
    trust, explainability, and interaction coherence in complex web interfaces without replacing native
    platform semantics.
  </p>

  <h2>The papers</h2>
  <ol class="research-list">
    {
      RESEARCH_PAPERS.map((p) => (
        <li>
          <a href={p.href}><strong>{p.n}. {p.title}</strong></a>
          <span class="rl-contrib">{p.contribution}</span>
        </li>
      ))
    }
  </ol>

  <p>
    See also the running <a href="/research/references">bibliography</a>. The first paper names the
    paradigm; the rest prove it in specific interface domains — reading, evidence/trust, accessibility,
    runtime architecture, authoring, data binding, and diagnostics.
  </p>

  <style>
    .lede { font-size: 1.15rem; opacity: 0.95; }
    .research-list { list-style: none; padding: 0; display: grid; gap: 0.9rem; }
    .research-list li { display: grid; gap: 0.15rem; }
    .research-list .rl-contrib { opacity: 0.8; font-size: 0.95rem; }
  </style>
</ResearchLayout>
